    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"## Conclusions\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"**Best model and why.** The **MLP** achieves the best results (balanced accuracy 0.852, macro-F1 0.873), ahead of kNN (0.817) and SVM-RBF (0.809), which perform similarly. All three sklearn models clearly outperform the from-scratch Gaussian classifier (macro-F1 0.503). The Gaussian's poor performance is itself informative: it assumes each class follows a multivariate normal distribution, but our features are mostly counts and binary flags with strongly skewed distributions, so the Gaussian assumption is violated — which explains the drop.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"**Which classes are misclassified the most.** From the MLP confusion matrix, per-class recall is: benign ~96%, defacement ~91%, malware ~83%, phishing ~71%. The hardest class is **phishing**, most often confused with **benign** (106 out of ~440 phishing URLs predicted as benign). This confirms the hypothesis formed during EDA: malware is the most identifiable class (thanks to `has_ip` and `digit_ratio`), while the phishing/benign boundary is the hardest, because phishing URLs lexically imitate legitimate sites. The strong agreement between the EDA prediction and the model's actual errors supports the validity of our feature design.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"**Does the MLP justify its complexity?** Yes, but with nuance. The MLP gains only about 5-6 macro-F1 points over the best simple model (kNN, 0.817). The improvement is real but moderate, and kNN remains a strong, much simpler and more interpretable baseline. So the added complexity of the MLP is worthwhile if the goal is maximum accuracy, but a simpler model would be a reasonable choice if interpretability or training cost mattered more.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"**Most serious errors (security standpoint).** The most dangerous mistakes are malicious URLs classified as benign (false negatives): 106 phishing, 23 defacement and 7 malware were labeled benign. Notably, malware almost never slips through (only 7 cases), while phishing is the main security weakness — consistent with it being the hardest class overall.\"\n",
    "   ],\n",
